WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
James O'Brien: Good morning everyone. Let's do our standup. Dave, you want to start?

00:00:05.500 --> 00:00:28.000
Dave Rossi: Yeah. So yesterday was a rough one. Stripe had an outage starting around 8 AM and our retry handler completely fell over. The problem was the fixed three-second retry interval. When Stripe went down, every single failed payment started retrying every three seconds. When Stripe came back up, we basically DDoS'd ourselves with all the queued retries hitting at once.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:45.500
Dave Rossi: I deployed a hotfix by noon. Replaced the fixed delay with exponential backoff and jitter. The formula is base delay times two to the power of the attempt count, plus a random jitter. Also added a circuit breaker that trips after five consecutive failures. Once the circuit breaker is open, we stop retrying for thirty seconds before half-opening.

00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:58.000
Dave Rossi: Today I'm going to clean up the code a bit and write proper tests. I also filed PAY-219 to audit all the other retry patterns in the codebase. I know the webhook receiver and the invoice generator both have the same fixed-interval problem.

00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:08.000
James O'Brien: Good work getting that fixed quickly, Dave. Can you lead the incident debrief on Wednesday? I want the whole team there so we can learn from this.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
Dave Rossi: Sure, I'll put together a timeline and root cause analysis.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:14.500
James O'Brien: Lisa, you're next.

00:01:14.500 --> 00:01:30.000
Lisa Park: So I was the one who first spotted the alerts yesterday morning from Datadog. I flagged it to Dave and helped monitor while he was working on the fix. Today Dave assigned me PAY-206, which is adding a dead letter queue for failed webhook events. Right now when a webhook processing fails, the event is just silently dropped. We need a way to capture and reprocess those.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:40.500
Lisa Park: I'm going to dig into the webhook receiver code today. I haven't worked in that part of the codebase before, so I might have some questions for Dave as I go. My plan is to use SQS for the dead letter queue with a retry Lambda.

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:46.000
Dave Rossi: Happy to pair on it if you get stuck. The webhook verification flow is a bit tricky.

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:49.000
James O'Brien: Marcus?

00:01:49.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Marcus Thompson: I'm heads-down on the GitHub Actions migration. Had a good sync with Dave yesterday after the architecture review. I understand the billing service's database migration steps now. The production workflow should be ready for testing by tomorrow.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:09.500
Marcus Thompson: I'm also keeping an eye on the rate limiting prototypes. I'll have both token bucket and sliding window implementations ready by Thursday as Sarah asked.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
James O'Brien: Priya?

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Priya Sharma: I'm finishing up the TransactionList component today. Pagination and filtering are done. I'm adding the sorting logic now. After that, I'm going to build the StatusBadge and DataTable shared components that the rest of the dashboard will use.

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:32.500
Priya Sharma: No blockers. Should have both components done by end of day tomorrow.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
James O'Brien: Sarah, anything from you?

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:50.000
Sarah Chen: Just a reminder that the CI/CD migration is the top priority this sprint. I want Jenkins fully deprecated by end of sprint. Also, I've started drafting the architecture decision record for the rate limiting approach — I'll finalize it after Thursday's review once we've made the final call.

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:58.000
James O'Brien: Great. Thanks everyone. Dave, don't forget the incident debrief is tomorrow at 2 PM. Everyone please attend.
